                         <div><H1 align="center">LearnMode with Lawson</h1></div>
                         <br />
                         <hr />
                         <br />
                        
        
         <div class="callout-content">
         <p>Lawson, an ERP (enterprise resource planning) system integrates with ImageNow in business processes such as Human Resources and Accounts Payable among others.</p>
         <br />
<p>This page describes the different approaches to learning a Lawson form. For purposes of this page and the related articles, the word “form” refers to a screen in Lawson, rather than an ImageNow eForm. Once a Lawson form is successfully learned, it can be used to drive searching within ImageNow using a <a href="https://perceptivesoftware.secure.force.com/articles/Support_Articles/Article-000015696?retURL=%2Fapex%2Fknowledge%3Fproductdocument%3Dtrue%26producthelp%3Dtrue%26s%3Dview%2Baction%2Bfilter%26supportarticle%3Dtrue%26supporttroubleshooting%3Dtrue%26video%3Dtrue&popup=false%3FretURL=https%3A//perceptivesoftware.secure.force.com/knowledge%3Fproductdocument=true&producthelp=true&s=view+action+filter&supportarticle=true&supporttroubleshooting=true&video=true&refURL=http%3A%2F%2Fperceptivesoftware.secure.force.com%2Fknowledge">view action filter.</a>.
</p>
         <br />
         <p></p>
         <br/>
         <p><b>Note: </b> To learn a Lawson form, you will need the global privilege to Manage Application Plans within ImageNow. </p>
         <br/>
         <br/>
         <h2><font color= "FF9933">Lawson Portal (non-shifting values)</font></h2>
         <br/>
         <ul>
         <li><h3>Internet Explorer (IE) LearnMode method</h3></li>
         <br />
         <p>If there is a “hard anchor” point on a form, one that does not move and is consistent across all logins, use the dictionary data element definition of the IE method to capture data values. For details, refer to the <a href="https://perceptivesoftware.secure.force.com/articles/ProductHelp/Help-40001105?popup=true">Define a dictionary data element using Internet Explorer</a> topic in Product Documentation.</p>
         </ul>
         <br />
         <h2><font color= "FF9933">Lawson Portal (shifting values condition exists)</font></h2>
         <br />
         One challenge to learning Lawson Portal is that the values may shift within the application layer depending on a user’s role, even though the values appear in the same location on the form. To account for the shifting values, the following approaches are presented in order of effectiveness.
         <br/>
         <br/>
         
         <ul>
         
         <li><h3>Custom HTML tags</h3></li>
         <br/>
        If the HTML locations shift on the Lawson form, consider <a href="https://perceptivesoftware.secure.force.com/articles/Support_Articles/Article-000015576?popup=true">embedding hidden HTML tags</a>. Using anchored hidden HTML tags can be a quick approach for learning a form.
         <br />
         <br />
        
         <li><h3>Scripting with Internet Explorer LearnMode functions</h3></li>
         <br/>
         On occasion, scripting is a necessary strategy to capture shifting data values when the use of hidden HTML tags is not an option. A VBScript can be designed to specifically locate and retrieve data from an IE element table. The article <a href="https://perceptivesoftware.secure.force.com/articles/Support_Articles/Article-00004367?popup=true">Using IE LearnMode VBScript functions</a> contains instructions for using a script to capture shifting data values.
          <br />
         <br />
        
         <li><h3>AppGetData function with AccExplorer</h3></li>
         <br/>
        If IE LearnMode VBScript functions are not an option, then AccExplorer can be used to create a VBScript with the AppGetData function to locate needed values. Refer to the <a href="https://perceptivesoftware.secure.force.com/articles/Support_Articles/Article-000015686?popup=true"> Learning a business application with shifting values using the AppGetData function</a> article in Knowledgebase for more information.
         <br />
         <br />
        
         <li><h3>Viewpoint </h3></li>
         <br/>
        The Viewpoint method can be used to learn a Lawson form with either Internet Explorer or Mozilla Firefox web browsers. Viewpoint is a good option under the f
        lowing conditions: 
         <br/>
         <br/>
         <ol>
       
          <li>The linking information can be seen on the form without scrolling.</li> 
          <li>Windows display settings are consistent, since Viewpoint is dependent on window mapping coordinates. </li> 
          <li>For browser-delivered applications, the locations of browser toolbars are standardized. With toolbars standardized, this method can successfully obtain needed data values for linking.</li> 
         <br/> 
          
         </ol>
         
         Refer to <a href="https://perceptivesoftware.secure.force.com/articles/Support_Articles/Article-000015659?popup=true">Tips for learning a browser-delivered application using the Viewpoint method </a> in Knowledgebase.
         <br />
            <br />
              
         <li><H3>HyperLearn</H3></li>
         <br/>
          Lastly, if the Lawson form cannot be learned with the previous options HyperLearn can be employed. Refer to <a href="https://perceptivesoftware.secure.force.com/articles/Support_Articles/Article-000015524?popup=true">HyperLearn Overview</a> in Knowledgebase for tips when using HyperLearn.  <br/>
         <br/>
 
         </ul>         
